{{Infobox journal | cover = Econdevelopcover.gif | discipline = [[Economics]], [[culture]] | editor = Marcel Fafchamps | abbreviation = Econ. Dev. Cult. Change | publisher = [[University of Chicago Press]] | country = United States | frequency = Quarterly | history = 1952–present | website = http://www.journals.uchicago.edu/edcc | impact = 1.188 | impact-year = 2017 | ISSN = 0013-0079 | JSTOR = 00130079 | eISSN = 1539-2988 | OCLC = 1567393 | LCCN = 56015874 | CODEN = EDCCAF }} '''''Economic Development and Cultural Change (EDCC)''''' publishes studies that use modern [[theoretical]] and [[empirical]] approaches to examine both the determinants and the effects of various dimensions of [[economic development]] and [[cultural change]]. It covers all aspects of the [[economics]] of [[developing country|developing countries]], including [[education reform]], [[immigration]], [[debt bondage]], [[ethnic group|ethnicity]], [[redistribution of wealth|land redistribution]], and [[economic development]] and [[culture|cultural change]]. ''EDCC''’s focus is on empirical papers with analytic underpinnings, concentrating on micro-level [[evidence]], that use appropriate data to test theoretical models and explore [[policy]] impacts related to [[economic development]].
The major founder of the journal was [[Bert F. Hoselitz]] who served as editor from 1952 until 1985.<ref>[http://chronicle.uchicago.edu/950309/hoselitz.shtml Obituary: Bert Hoselitz, Economics]. ''The University of Chicago Chronicle'', 14:13; March 9, 1995</ref> The journal was established at the [[University of Chicago]]'s Center for Research on Economic Development and Cultural Change. The Center's board and the journal's founders took the view that [[interdisciplinarity|interdisciplinary research]] would be required to understand issues of economic development.
