{{Other uses2|Fish}}

'''Fis phenomenon''' is a phenomenon of child [[language acquisition]] that demonstrates that perception of [[phoneme]]s occurs earlier than the ability of the child to produce those phonemes.  It is also illustrative of a larger theme in child language acquisition: that skills in [[language comprehension|linguistic comprehension]] generally precede corresponding skills in [[language production|linguistic production]].

The name comes from an incident reported in 1960 by [[Jean Berko Gleason|J. Berko]] and [[Roger Brown (psychologist)|R. Brown]].<ref>{{cite book | chapter = Psycholinguistic Research Methods | author = [[Jean Berko Gleason|J. Berko]] and [[Roger Brown (psychologist)|R. Brown]] | title = Handbook of Research methods in [[Child Development]] | editor = P. Mussen | location = New York | publisher = John Wiley | year = 1960 | pages = 517–557 }}</ref> A child referred to his inflatable plastic fish as a ''fis''. However, when adults asked him, "Is this your ''fis''?" he rejected the statement. When he was asked, "Is this your fish?" he responded, "Yes, my fis."   This shows that although the child could not produce the phoneme {{IPA|/ʃ/}}, he could perceive it as being different from the phoneme {{IPA|/s/}}. 
In some cases, the sounds produced by the child are actually acoustically different, but not significantly enough for others to distinguish<ref>[[Victoria Fromkin|Fromkin]], V. (Ed.) (2000). Linguistics: An Introduction to Linguistic Theory. Malden, MA: Blackwell Publishing. {{ISBN|0-631-19711-7}}. Chapter 7: [[Phonology]].</ref> since the language in question does not make such contrasts.

